        },
        {
          "id": 24436,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">GLUT 2</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">During a pediatric rotation, a medical student observes the management of a child presenting with acute gastroenteritis and signs of dehydration. The attending physician prescribes oral rehydration solution (ORS). The student learns that the efficacy of ORS is partly due to its facilitation of glucose absorption, which in turn enhances electrolyte and water uptake in the intestines. Which glucose transporter is primarily responsible for the glucose absorption facilitated by ORS in the intestinal mucosa? </span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1100601",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29809,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) SGLT-1 </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Absorption</strong> from<strong> intestinal lumen </strong>into<strong> intestinal cell </strong>is by <strong>Sodium Dependent Glucose</strong></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/02/picture1.jpg\" style=\"height:243px; width:500px\" /></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Transporter-1 (SGLT-1),</strong> cotransport mechanism (secondary active transport) </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A<strong> membrane bound carrier protein</strong> is involved, which<strong> carries glucose,</strong> along with <strong>sodium </strong>&rarr; sodium is <strong>later</strong> expelled by the <strong>sodium pump</strong> with <strong>utilization of energy. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The transporter in the<strong> intestine is SGLT-1 </strong>involved in<strong> glucose-galactose malabsorption</strong> and in the <strong>kidney is SGLT-2 </strong>which is<strong> defective </strong>in <strong>congenital renal glycosuria</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Clinical application: Common treatment for<strong> diarrhoea is oral rehydration fluid,</strong> which contains <strong>both glucose and sodium</strong> &rarr; allows <strong>absorption of sodium</strong> to <strong>replenish body sodium chloride levels</strong> and<strong> glucose</strong> to provide<strong> energy. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B.&nbsp; SGLT-2:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> SGLT-2 is<strong> defective </strong>in<strong> congenital renal glycosuria</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. GLUT 4:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp; <strong>Insulin-mediated glucose uptake.</strong> Involved in <strong>Type 2 diabetes mellitus</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D.&nbsp; GLUT 2:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong> Enables the pancreas</strong> to <strong>monitor the glucose level,</strong> thereby adjusts the<strong> rate of insulin secretion.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>SGLT 1</strong> (<strong>sodium-glucose cotransporter 1</strong>) is responsible for the <strong>absorption of glucose</strong> in the <strong>small intestine.</strong> It<strong> cotransports sodium</strong> and <strong>glucose from the intestinal lumen </strong>into<strong> enterocytes</strong>, thereby <strong>facilitating the absorption of water and electrolytes,</strong> which is the principle behind the <strong>effectiveness of ORS.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Vasudevan 9/e: 106.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
