        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) A as well as R are right, and R is a correct explanation of A</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">GLUT-4 and Insulin:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Glucose uptake into muscle and adipose tissue</strong> is fully controlled by <strong>insulin</strong>, which is <strong>secreted </strong>by the <strong>beta cells of pancreas </strong>in response to an <strong>increased glucose concentration</strong> in the<strong> blood. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In fasting state</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">, the <strong>glucose transporter of muscle and adipose tissue (GLUT-4)</strong> is in <strong>intracellular vesicles.</strong> As <strong>insulin</strong> <strong>secretion falls</strong> in the fasting state, the <strong>receptors are internalized,</strong> <strong>reducing glucose uptake.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In Fed state:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> An <strong>early response to insulin,</strong> migration of these <strong>vesicles to the cell surface </strong>takes place, where they <strong>fuse</strong> with the <strong>plasma membrane,</strong> exposing <strong>active glucose transporters. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">These <strong>insulin-sensitive tissues</strong> only take up <strong>glucose from the bloodstream </strong>to any significant extent in the <strong>presence of</strong> the <strong>hormone. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">After <strong>overnight fasting, insulin</strong> levels in the body are <strong>low</strong>. In<strong> insulin-sensitive tissues </strong>like <strong>adipocytes, low insulin levels</strong> lead to a <strong>decrease</strong> in the number of <strong>glucose transporters (such as GLUT4) </strong>present on the <strong>cell membrane </strong>because<strong> insulin </strong>is required to stimulate the <strong>translocation </strong>of these <strong>transporters </strong>from the <strong>intracellular stores to the cell surface.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/e p192.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
