        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) GLUT 5</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Here the <strong>patient&rsquo;s liver enzymes are normal </strong>and her <strong>symptoms aggravated </strong>with<strong> intake of fruit juices</strong>. So, <strong>most likely </strong>the <strong>child</strong> is having an<strong> inability to absorb fructose. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Since <strong>removal of even cow&rsquo;s milk</strong> from <strong>her diet</strong> did <strong>not</strong> eliminate <strong>her symptoms,</strong> hence <strong>lactase deficiency</strong> is <strong>ruled out. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>GLUT 5</strong> is the <strong>primary transporter of fructose </strong>in the<strong> intestine</strong> and <strong>its deficiency </strong>leads to an<strong> inability to absorb fructose</strong> in the<strong> gut</strong> ​​&rarr;<strong> fructose</strong> <strong>acts</strong> as a <strong>substrate</strong> for <strong>bacterial metabolism &rarr; Produces gases</strong> (<strong>hydrogen</strong>) and <strong>organic acids.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. SGLT:&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Sodium Dependent Glucose Transporter-1 (SGLT-1) is the<strong> transporter</strong> in the<strong> intestine</strong> involved in <strong>glucose-galactose</strong> <strong>malabsorption</strong>. For<strong> diarrhoea</strong>, <strong>ORS </strong>is given which contains<strong> both glucose and sodium </strong>&rarr; allows <strong>absorption of sodium</strong> to <strong>replenish</strong> <strong>body sodium chloride</strong> levels and <strong>glucose to provide energy.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Isomaltose:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp; he <strong>cells of brush border </strong>of intestine contain <strong>sucrase, maltase, Isomaltose and lactase</strong> &rarr; which<strong> hydrolyze</strong> the corresponding <strong>disaccharides into monosaccharides</strong>, which are then <strong>absorbed.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option D. &nbsp;Lactase:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Deficiency of lactase</strong> leads to <strong>lactose intolerance</strong> &rarr;<strong> accumulation of lactose </strong>in the gut &rarr; <strong>Irritant diarrhoea </strong>and <strong>flatulence.</strong> Treatment- <strong>withdrawn milk temporarily.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>GLUT 5</strong> is a <strong>fructose</strong> transporter expressed in the<strong> intestinal mucosa.</strong> A <strong>deficiency or defect in GLUT 5 </strong>would lead to <strong>fructose</strong> <strong>malabsorption</strong>, presenting with symptoms such as<strong> abdominal pain, distension, and gas formation </strong>after <strong>consuming fructose.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Vasudevan 9/e: 106-107.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
