      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">A 42-year-old visits a local clinic for a routine check-up. The healthcare provider at the clinic performs an Oral Glucose Tolerance Test (OGTT) to assess his glucose metabolism. The results are plotted on a graph showing plasma glucose levels over time after a glucose load. Based on the graph shown, what is your interpretation of the patient’s OGTT results?</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><img class=\"image_resized\" style=\"aspect-ratio:1080/709;width:93.73%;\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/Picture2%20(2).jpg\" width=\"1080\" height=\"709\"></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q7688402",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29814,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Correct Answer: B. Overt Diabetes mellitus</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Explanation:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Based on the graph provided, which shows plasma glucose levels after a glucose load:</span></p><ul><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The normal curve rises to about 140 mg/dL and then returns to baseline (~90 mg/dL) within 2 hours.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The diabetic curve spikes up to ~300 mg/dL at 1 hour and remains significantly elevated (well above 200 mg/dL) even at 2 hours.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">the Oral Glucose Tolerance Test (OGTT) is interpreted as follows:</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Normal: Fasting glucose &lt; 100 mg/dL; 2-hour post-load &lt; 140 mg/dL.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Impaired glucose tolerance: fasting glucose 100-126 mg/dl; 2-hour post-load 140–199 mg/dL.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Diabetes mellitus: Fasting ≥ 126 mg/dL or 2-hour post-load ≥ 200 mg/dL .</span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/120.png\" width=\"867\" height=\"166\"></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Interpretation</strong>:</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The patient's OGTT pattern on the graph matches the diabetic curve (persistent elevation above 200 mg/dL even after 2 hours), clearly meeting criteria for overt diabetes mellitus.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></span></p><ul><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A. Symptoms of Diabetes mellitus with inconclusive blood glucose values</strong>: This applies when symptoms are present but glucose levels don’t conclusively meet diagnostic thresholds (not the case here, where the glucose is clearly high).</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Diabetic nephropathy</strong>: This is a complication of diabetes involving kidney damage and is not diagnosed by OGTT . OGTT assesses glucose metabolism, not kidney function.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D. Follow-up of a case of Diabetes mellitus</strong>: OGTT is not recommended for follow-up of known diabetes cases. HbA1c, fasting glucose, and self-monitoring of blood glucose are the preferred methods for monitoring glycemic control in diagnosed patients.</span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Educational Objectives:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Difference between normal, impaired, and diabetic glucose values.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/121.png\" width=\"866\" height=\"164\"></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ref</strong>: Harper 30/e:&nbsp; p 195-196, 205.&nbsp;</span></p>",
